# TypeScript Generics

Generics are **type parameters** — placeholders that get filled in when you use a function or class. The mental model: a generic is like a variable, but for types instead of values. When you call `identity<string>('hello')`, TypeScript replaces every `T` with `string` and checks accordingly.

```
Generic function call flow:

function identity<T>(x: T): T  ← T is a type variable
                   ▲
                   │  filled in at the call site
identity<string>('hello')      ← T = string
identity<number>(42)           ← T = number
identity('hello')              ← T inferred = string (no annotation needed)

  Result type = T = whatever was passed in
  No any, no loss of type info
```

## Why generics beat `any`

```ts
// With any — loses type information
function first_any(arr: any[]): any {
  return arr[0];
}
const x = first_any([1, 2, 3]);  // x is 'any' — TS knows nothing
x.toUpperCase();                 // ✓ compiles but crashes at runtime

// With generic — preserves type
function first<T>(arr: T[]): T {
  return arr[0];
}
const y = first([1, 2, 3]);      // y is 'number'
y.toUpperCase();                 // ✗ Error — number has no toUpperCase
```

## Generic Functions

```ts
// Basic — one type param
function wrap<T>(value: T): { value: T } {
  return { value };
}

// Multiple type params
function pair<A, B>(a: A, b: B): [A, B] {
  return [a, b];
}
const p = pair('hello', 42);  // [string, number]

// Arrow function syntax
const identity = <T>(x: T): T => x;

// In .tsx files, disambiguate from JSX:
const identity = <T,>(x: T): T => x;  // trailing comma avoids JSX confusion
```

## Generic Interfaces and Types

```ts
// Generic interface
interface Box<T> {
  value: T;
  transform: (x: T) => T;
}

const numBox: Box<number> = {
  value: 42,
  transform: x => x * 2,
};

// Generic type alias — common for data structures
type Result<T, E = Error> = 
  | { ok: true;  value: T }
  | { ok: false; error: E };

function divide(a: number, b: number): Result<number> {
  if (b === 0) return { ok: false, error: new Error('divide by zero') };
  return { ok: true, value: a / b };
}
```

## Generic Classes

```ts
class Stack<T> {
  private items: T[] = [];

  push(item: T): void {
    this.items.push(item);
  }

  pop(): T | undefined {
    return this.items.pop();
  }

  peek(): T | undefined {
    return this.items[this.items.length - 1];
  }

  get size(): number {
    return this.items.length;
  }
}

const numStack = new Stack<number>();
numStack.push(1);
numStack.push(2);
const top = numStack.peek();  // type: number | undefined
```

## Constraints — `extends` on type parameters

Constraints tell TypeScript: 'T can be any type, but it must have at least these fields.'

```
Constraint mental model:

function getLength<T extends { length: number }>(x: T): number
                      ▲
                      │ T must have a .length property

getLength([1, 2, 3]);     // T = number[]    ✓ arrays have .length
getLength('hello');        // T = string      ✓ strings have .length
getLength({ length: 5 }); // T = {length:5}  ✓ has .length
getLength(42);             // ✗ Error — number has no .length
```

```ts
// Constraint: T must be an object
function clone<T extends object>(obj: T): T {
  return { ...obj } as T;
}

// Constraint: K must be a key of T
function getProperty<T, K extends keyof T>(obj: T, key: K): T[K] {
  return obj[key];
}

const user = { name: 'Alice', age: 30 };
const name = getProperty(user, 'name');  // type: string
const age  = getProperty(user, 'age');   // type: number
getProperty(user, 'email');              // ✗ Error — 'email' not in typeof user
```

## `keyof` and Indexed Access Types

```ts
interface User { name: string; age: number; email: string; }

type UserKey = keyof User;        // 'name' | 'age' | 'email'
type NameType = User['name'];     // string  (indexed access)
type AgeType  = User['age'];      // number

// Dynamic indexed access with generic
type ValueOf<T, K extends keyof T> = T[K];
type EmailType = ValueOf<User, 'email'>;  // string
```

```
keyof mental model:

interface User
  │
  ├── name: string    → 'name'
  ├── age: number     → 'age'
  └── email: string   → 'email'

keyof User = 'name' | 'age' | 'email'   ← union of all property name literals

User['name'] = string                    ← type of User.name property
```

## Default Type Parameters

```ts
// Default: if no type arg given, use Error
type Result<T, E = Error> = 
  | { ok: true; value: T }
  | { ok: false; error: E };

type StringResult = Result<string>;        // E defaults to Error
type CustomResult = Result<string, string>; // E is string
```

## Generic Complexity Cheatsheet

| Pattern | Syntax | When to use |
|---|---|---|
| Basic | `<T>` | Single input/output type |
| Multi | `<A, B>` | Pair or transform functions |
| Constrained | `<T extends X>` | Require a minimum shape |
| Key constraint | `K extends keyof T` | Type-safe property access |
| Default | `<T, E = Error>` | Optional second type with fallback |
| Indexed access | `T[K]` | Look up property type dynamically |

## Common Pitfalls
- Overusing generics when `any` would be clearer — not every function needs a type parameter
- Forgetting the trailing comma in `.tsx` files: `<T,>` to avoid JSX parsing ambiguity
- Constraining too loosely (`<T extends object>`) vs. too tightly (`<T extends User>`)
- Assuming `T extends string` means T IS string — T could be a string literal type`'hello'`
- Using `as T` to force-cast instead of properly constraining — defeats the purpose

## Connections
- **ts-utility-types** — Partial, Pick, Omit are all generic types
- **ts-advanced-types** — conditional types and mapped types are parameterised with generics
- **ts-interfaces-types** — generic interfaces and the `keyof` / indexed access operators
- **react-hooks** — useState<T>, useRef<T> and custom hooks use generics extensively

